{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-91595e1810b328a6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tRPPNET: PERCEPTUALLY-GROUPED RHYTHM-PITCH PRIMITIVES\n2\tFOR LONG-TERM STRUCTURE MELODY GENERATION VIA\n3\tBOUNDARY-AWARE MODELING\n4\tTieyao Zhang1\n5\tYuke Liu1\n6\tJiaxing Yu2\n7\t2\n8\t2\n9\tXinda Wu\n10\tKejun Zhang\n11\tGenfang Chen1,3\n12\t1\n13\tZhejiang Conservatory of Music, Hangzhou, China\n14\t2\n15\tZhejiang University, Hangzhou, China\n16\t3\n17\tZJU-ZJCM MusicAI Lab, Hangzhou, China\n18\ttieyaozhang@stu.zjcm.edu.cn, keke@stu.zjcm.edu.cn, yujx@zju.edu.cn,\n19\twuxinda@zju.edu.cn, zhangkejun@zju.edu.cn, cgf@zjcm.edu.cn\n20\t\n21\tarXiv:2607.19776v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n22\t\n23\tABSTRACT\n24\t\n25\tThey require no hand-crafted domain rules and can automatically extract knowledge from large-scale data; their\n26\teffectiveness has been validated across multiple disciplines\n27\t[6–10].\n28\tHowever, long-term structure modeling in symbolic\n29\tmusic remains challenging [11–13]. Existing methods\n30\toperate within linear sequence frameworks where attention mechanisms capture long-range token correlations yet\n31\tfail to learn explicit associations between non-adjacent\n32\tbut functionally similar structural units; meanwhile, this\n33\ttask requires integrating music theory, computational modeling, psychology, and neuroscience [14]. Both factors\n34\tjointly constrain effective learning of hierarchical logic, biasing models toward local statistical patterns and limiting\n35\tlong-term structure generation quality.\n36\tRecent works integrate computational modeling with\n37\tmusic theory to improve long-term coherence through explicit structural boundaries and thematic features, such as\n38\tMuseformer [15] with its hierarchical attention mechanism, Theme Transformer [16] with thematic material retrieval, and MELONS [17] and PopMNet [18] with graphstructured thematic variation encoding. However, these\n39\tmethods rely on fixed bar-level units. Psychological evidence shows that listeners perceive structural boundaries\n40\tthrough acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similaritybased grouping [19–21], rather than fixed metric segmentation. This mismatch hinders listeners’ perceptual grouping of the generated structure, thereby reducing overall\n41\tmusical coherence.\n42\tTo address this problem, we propose a hierarchical\n43\tmelody generation framework, RPPNet 1 . It is based on\n44\tan autoregressive architecture and splits generation into\n45\tan RPP-level generation stage and a Note-level generation stage. Both stages use a Transformer encoder-decoder\n46\t[22].\n47\tDrawing on music theory and cognitive psychology,\n48\twe use three perceptual dimensions—acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity relations—and rhythmic structure analysis [20, 23, 24] to design a heuristic algorithm.\n49\t\n50\tExisting symbolic music generation models typically use\n51\tbars as the basic structural unit. However, human perception of musical phrases often does not align with notated\n52\tbar lines, leading to long-term structural fragmentation.\n53\tThis paper proposes RPPNet—a two-stage deep learning\n54\tarchitecture with variable structural boundaries. It first\n55\tgenerates variable-length Rhythm-Pitch Primitive (RPP)\n56\tsequences, where each RPP encodes note count, rhythm,\n57\tand contour; then decodes the RPP sequences into concrete notes. The grouping of RPPs is automatically derived\n58\tfrom acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity perception based on music psychology. Experiments show that\n59\tmelodies generated by RPPNet are superior in both longterm structure and musicality, with significant improvements across all subjective evaluation dimensions. Ablation studies confirm that the performance gain stems from\n60\tthe structural correctness of the psychological representation, rather than from model capacity. This work offers\n61\tan interdisciplinary perspective for music generation, integrating music theory, computational modeling, and music\n62\tpsychology.\n63\t1. INTRODUCTION\n64\tSymbolic melody generation is a core direction of generative AI in art [1]. In recent years, text-to-audio models have achieved notable results and can generate complete songs, yet they do not allow fine-grained user control [2–4]. Symbolic music, in contrast, enables precise\n65\tcontrol over melody, harmony, and other elements, holding\n66\ta central position in human-AI co-creation. Consequently,\n67\tthis direction continues to attract significant attention from\n68\tboth academia and industry [5].\n69\tIn recent years, researchers have drawn on language\n70\tmodels from natural language processing to capture\n71\tlong-term dependencies in music and achieve structured\n72\tmelody generation. Such methods offer an end-to-end\n73\tframework, excellent representation learning ability, and\n74\tthe potential to generate sequences of arbitrary length.\n75\t\n76\t1 The source code is available at:\n77\thttps://github.com/\n78\tKreuzter0421/RPPNet-PyTorch.git\n79\t\n80\t1\n81\t\n82\t\fThis algorithm represents a melody as a sequence of nonequidistant rhythm-pitch primitives (RPPs).\n83\tThe RPP-level stage employs decoupled serial prediction for autoregressive RPP generation, constructing longterm structure; the Note-level stage decodes RPPs into\n84\tMIDI notes via time-scale expansion mapping. Unlike barbased approaches (e.g., Museformer, MELONS), RPPNet\n85\treplaces fixed bars with perceptually-driven flexible grouping units—the first hierarchical model to do so, grounded\n86\tin psychological evidence that phrase boundaries often\n87\tmisalign with notated bar lines.\n88\tOur contributions are as follows:\n89\t1. We propose RPPNet, a two-stage hierarchical framework with a novel perception-driven structural representation. It replaces fixed bar-level boundaries\n90\twith flexible rhythm-pitch primitives grouped by\n91\tacoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity perception.\n92\t2. We propose an automatic grouping algorithm that\n93\tderives structural boundaries without explicit annotations. Controlled ablations demonstrate that performance gains stem from perceptual grouping principles rather than model capacity.\n94\t3. The proposed time-scale expansion mapping bridges\n95\tdiscrete RPP events and continuous Note-level generation, with decoupled serial prediction ensuring\n96\tstrict alignment between generated notes and the\n97\tRPP sequences.\n98\t4. Experimental results show that RPPNet outperforms\n99\texisting baselines in long-term structural coherence\n100\tand musicality.\n101\t2. RELATED WORK\n102\t2.1 Long Sequence Symbolic Music Generation\n103\tSymbolic music generation performs algorithmic composition by modeling discrete musical events, encoded\n104\tin formats including MIDI, MusicXML, and ABC notation.Early research focused on local sequential dependency\n105\tmodeling: N-gram Markov chains predict the next event\n106\tbased on joint preceding events [25], yet can only capture short-range dependencies and fail to model deep hierarchical structures. HMM introduce latent states to implicitly control token distributions [26, 27], while dynamic\n107\tBayesian networks further explicitly model deep dependencies [28].\n108\tIn recent years, deep neural network generative models have achieved significant advances in symbolic music. From RNNs [29], VAEs [30], and GANs [31], to\n109\tTransformers [32–34], modeling capabilities have steadily\n110\tincreased. However, the quadratic complexity of Transformer self-attention, compounded by the long sequence\n111\tnature of symbolic music, poses severe challenges for\n112\tmodeling dependencies spanning hundreds of bars.\n113\tThis challenge stems from standard tokenization strategies, where a single piece can reach thousands to tens of\n114\t\n115\tthousands of tokens [35], severely weakening long-term\n116\tdependency modeling [36, 37]. Even when subsequent\n117\tstudies introduce compound tokens (e.g., Compound Word\n118\t[38], Octuple [39]) to compress sequence length, models\n119\tstill struggle to capture thematic repetition and variation\n120\tspanning dozens of bars—the core difficulty of long-term\n121\tstructure modeling.\n122\t2.2 Structure modeling guided by music theory\n123\tTo address the challenges of long-range structural modeling in music, researchers have attempted to incorporate\n124\tmusic theory priors into model design to guide globally\n125\tcoherent generation. The relevant methods can be grouped\n126\tinto three categories.\n127\tStructure-aware attention: Optimizing attention distribution to efficiently extract musical structural features. For example, Museformer [15] combines fineand coarse-grained attention to capture bar-level structure; HAT [40] builds a harmony-aware hierarchical Transformer, using harmonic progressions to guide long-range\n128\tdependency modeling.\n129\tExternal structural prior injection: Explicitly introducing boundary or thematic features to constrain the generation process. Ref. [41] uses segmentation modules and\n130\tmulti-scale attention to inject structural boundary information, aiding long-form generation; Theme Transformer\n131\t[16] takes retrieved thematic material as a conditional sequence to enhance cross-segment thematic consistency.\n132\tHierarchical modeling and task decomposition: break\n133\tlong sequence generation into multi-level subtasks for\n134\tglobally controllable structure. MusicFramework [42] captures repetitive patterns via hierarchical representations\n135\tto support multi-level abstract melody generation; TMCGAN [43] explicitly models themes with a VAE-CGAN\n136\thybrid architecture, balancing global coherence and local\n137\tvariation; PhraseLDM [36] performs non-autoregressive\n138\tgeneration in a phrase-level latent space to yield 128bar multi-track music, alleviating long-term structure fragmentation. PopMNet [18] models internal dependencies\n139\tvia chord-melody graphs, while MELONS [17] combines\n140\tbar-level relational graphs with GraphRNN and Transformer for long-term structure modeling.\n141\tHowever, these methods all lack perceptual grounding\n142\tin structural segmentation. Neither explicit bar-level splitting nor implicit attention-based partitioning can capture\n143\tthe diversity and perceptual uncertainty of phrase boundaries, leading to structural degradation in long-term generation. Developing perceptually grounded, compact structural units for efficient structure-aware long-term structure\n144\tmodeling remains a core challenge.\n145\t2.3 Perceptual Theories of Musical Structure\n146\tThe challenge of modeling long-range structure in symbolic music [11–13] stems from the highly structured intrinsic nature of music: its elements are organized according to certain structural frameworks and expressed in\n147\thuman-understandable ways [14]. This framework exhibits significant multi-dimensional characteristics [44–\n148\t\n149\t\f46], encompassing not only basic components such as harmony and phrases but also interweaving cognitive organizational principles like similarity perception [21], making\n150\tthe analysis and modeling of its internal logic highly complex [47].\n151\tMusic psychology research shows that structural perception relies primarily on three mechanisms: (1) acoustic cues—using changes in intensity, pitch, duration, timbre, etc. to mark structural boundaries [20]; (2) auditory\n152\tinertia—based on the establishment and fulfillment of expectations for musical events [19]; (3) similarity perception—associating structural elements through motivic repetition and variation [21]. Together, these mechanisms reveal the hierarchical and theme-driven nature of musical\n153\tstructure.\n154\tDeliege [20] validated the psychological effectiveness\n155\tof grouping preference rules, confirming that acoustic\n156\tchanges in intensity and pitch serve as core cues for perceiving structural boundaries. Cooper and Meyer [19]\n157\tidentified auditory inertia as the organizing force of musical rhythm: listeners perceive continuous sound as a\n158\tdynamic structure based on psychological expectations,\n159\twhere deviations such as syncopation and rests create\n160\ttension. Lamont and Dibben [21] demonstrated through\n161\tcross-genre listening experiments that similarity judgments rely primarily on surface features such as texture\n162\tand pitch contour rather than deep structural assumptions,\n163\texhibiting significant contextual dependence.\n164\tTraditional music modeling is mostly based on noteor bar-level granularity, which hardly aligns with the actual mechanisms of structural perception. Drawing on\n165\tthe above psychological findings, this paper proposes\n166\ta heuristic algorithm that automatically analyzes monophonic melody structure based on acoustic cues, auditory\n167\tinertia, and similarity perception, and converts it into RPP\n168\tsequence data.\n169\t3. METHOD\n170\t3.1 Heuristic Segmentation of Rhythm-Pitch\n171\tPrimitive\n172\tTo construct cognitively grounded low-level structural\n173\tunits, we propose a heuristic melody segmentation algorithm that parses melodies into Rhythm-Pitch Primitives\n174\t(RPPs), each containing at most three notes to carry local\n175\tboundary information and support RPP-level generation,\n176\tlaying the foundation for subsequent hierarchical modeling.\n177\tPrimitives are defined by rhythmic patterns (five categories, e.g., iambic) and pitch contours (ascending, descending, etc.), as illustrated in Figure 1; evolutionary relationships between adjacent primitives are encoded via\n178\tmulti-hot vectors. Grouping employs dynamic programming to maximize the cumulative structural weight W (·) 2\n179\tof the parsed sequence (Algorithm 1), where W (·) scores\n180\t2 The complete formalization of W (·) is available in the repository\n181\t\n182\tmentioned above.\n183\t\n184\tAlgorithm 1 Dynamic Programming for RPP Grouping\n185\tInput: Note sequence P1:L , Weight function W (·)\n186\tOutput: Optimal RPP list R\n187\t1: if L ≤ 3 then\n188\t2:\n189\treturn {MakeRPP(P1:L )}\n190\t3: end if\n191\t4: dp[0] ← 0,\n192\tdp[1 . . . L] ← −∞\n193\t5: path[0 . . . L] ← ∅\n194\t6: for i = 1 to L do\n195\t7:\n196\tk ∗ ← arg max1≤k≤3 {dp[i − k] + W (Pi−k+1:i )}\n197\t8:\n198\tdp[i] ← dp[i − k ∗ ] + W (Pi−k∗ +1:i )\n199\t9:\n200\tpath[i] ← path[i − k ∗ ] ∪ {k ∗ }\n201\t10: end for\n202\t11: R ← ∅,\n203\tidx ← 1\n204\t12: for k ∈ path[L] do\n205\t13:\n206\tR ← R ∪ {MakeRPP(Pidx:idx+k−1 )}\n207\t14:\n208\tidx ← idx + k\n209\t15: end for\n210\t16: return R\n211\t\n212\teach note based on its metrical grid position, duration, and\n213\tsyncopation pattern.\n214\t3.2 Hierarchical Sequence Representation\n215\tTo overcome self-attention dilution in long sequences [15],\n216\twe propose a hierarchical generation architecture that\n217\tstrictly decouples the RPP-level and Note-level.\n218\t3.2.1 RPP-Level Representation\n219\tWe model the global structure as a sequence of RhythmPitch Primitives. The sequence is V = {v1 , . . . , vT }. Each\n220\tunit is explicitly defined as vi = {bi , pi , di , ri , mi }, where\n221\tbi , pi , and di denote the measure index, metrical position,\n222\tand duration respectively. The rhythmic pattern ri and\n223\tmelodic contour mi characterize the motif. This abstraction achieves significant temporal downsampling, enabling\n224\tefficient identification of form development without external priors.\n225\t3.2.2 Note-Level Representation\n226\tTo realize the RPP-level representation as Note-level outputs, we define a note sequence U = {u1 , . . . , uK } mapping to final MIDI events. Each unit uj = {bj , pj , dj , nj }\n227\tshares the aforementioned temporal grid, while nj explicitly defines the absolute pitch.\n228\t3.2.3 Compound Word Embedding Strategy\n229\tExtending the Compound Word parallel fusion concept\n230\t[48], the discrete attributes within vi and uj are independently mapped into dense vectors at each time step. These\n231\tvectors are subsequently aggregated into a unified hidden\n232\trepresentation via concatenation and linear projection.\n233\t3.3 Model\n234\tAs shown in Figure 2, our two-stage hierarchical generation framework decouples melody construction into RPPlevel structural planning and Note-level instantiation. This\n235\t\n236\t\fFigure 1. Example of RPP grouping (excerpt from Hey Jude). Colored legends indicate rhythmic types; black arrows\n237\tdenote melodic contour direction.\n238\tEqn (1):\n239\t\n240\tRPP<sos>\n241\tinput\n242\t\n243\tP (vt |h<t ) = P (post |h<t ) · P (dt , rt , mt |h<t , post ) (1)\n244\t\n245\tRPP-Level Generation\n246\t\n247\tLinear\n248\t\n249\tConcat\n250\t\n251\tGlobal Position\n252\t\n253\tLinear\n254\tDetails\n255\toutput\n256\t\n257\tRPP<sos>\n258\t\n259\tRPP1\n260\t\n261\tRPP2\n262\t\n263\t......\n264\t\n265\tRPPi\n266\t\n267\tNote<sos>\n268\t\n269\tinput\n270\t\n271\tinput\n272\t\n273\t3.3.2 Note-Level Generation\n274\t\n275\tNote-Level Generation\n276\toutput\n277\t\n278\tNote<sos>\n279\t\n280\tNote1\n281\t\n282\tThe model first predicts post solely from h<t . This position representation is subsequently mapped into a temporal\n283\tprior embedding and concatenated with h<t , enabling the\n284\tjoint prediction of duration, rhythmic pattern, and melodic\n285\tcontour under explicit temporal constraints.\n286\t\n287\tNote2\n288\t\n289\t......\n290\t\n291\tNotej\n292\t\n293\tFigure 2. The architecture of the proposed two-stage hierarchical generation framework. Melody construction is\n294\tstrictly decoupled into RPP-level structural planning and\n295\tNote-level note instantiation. The dashed box details the\n296\tdecoupled serial prediction mechanism deployed at the\n297\toutput end.\n298\t\n299\tmulti-resolution temporal representation effectively addresses the semantic disparity between abstract structural\n300\tdevelopment and Note-level symbolic generation.\n301\t3.3.1 RPP-Level Generation\n302\tThe RPP-level structural module aims to generate a longterm framework guiding musical development, featuring a\n303\tstandard Transformer encoder-decoder architecture as its\n304\tcore [34].\n305\tWhile employing compound representation inputs to\n306\tcompress sequence length, we replace traditional parallel\n307\tprediction with a decoupled serial prediction mechanism\n308\tat the output, highlighted by the dashed box in Figure 2.\n309\tGiven historical context features h<t at time step t, the\n310\tjoint probability of primitive vt is strictly decoupled into\n311\tthe marginal probability of temporal position post and conditional probabilities of detailed attributes, formulated in\n312\t\n313\tThe Note-level module decodes the RPP sequence into\n314\tconcrete note events via a Transformer encoder-decoder\n315\t[34]. We construct a time-scale expansion mapping that\n316\tbridges discrete RPP events and the continuous note-level\n317\ttime axis: for each primitive i, the absolute onset is computed as Tstart = bi × Rbar + pi , and its hidden state hi is\n318\tbroadcast across all grid steps within [Tstart , Tstart + di ).\n319\tThis allows the decoder to attend to structural memory via\n320\tcross-attention, ensuring strict alignment between output\n321\tnotes and the RPP-level skeleton.\n322\t4. EXPERIMENT\n323\t4.1 Dataset\n324\tWe adopt the MelodyNet dataset [49], comprising over\n325\t300,000 MIDI melodies from FreeMIDI, HookTheory,\n326\tBitMIDI, MuseScore, KernScores, and Kunstderfuge. After removing non-melody tracks and incomplete data,\n327\t274,300 melodies remain, split into train/validation/test\n328\tsets at a ratio of 18 : 1 : 1.\n329\t4.2 Compared Models\n330\tTo evaluate the structural awareness of RPPNet, we select two representative baseline models, human-composed\n331\tmelodies, and two framework variants to validate the specific contribution of the proposed heuristic RPP grouping:\n332\t• Museformer [15]: A long-sequence music generation model with fine- and coarse-grained attention.\n333\t\n334\t\f• MELONS [17]: A graph-sequence architecture that\n335\tmodels bar-level chord and melodic contours via line\n336\tgraphs to condition token generation.\n337\t• RPPNet-Real: A variant using ground-truth RPP sequences as RPP-level input, representing the theoretical ceiling of Note-level generation.\n338\t• RPPNet-Random-Grouped: An ablation baseline replacing heuristic RPP grouping with random segmentation while maintaining architectural consistency and length distribution alignment.\n339\tWe select Museformer [15] and MELONS [17] as primary baselines, as both exemplify fixed bar-level structural modeling — the exact assumption our work relaxes. MelodyGLM [49] is excluded because its pretrainfinetune paradigm confounds structural boundary design\n340\twith large-scale pretraining. PhraseLDM [36] is excluded\n341\tas it requires explicit phrase-level annotations unavailable\n342\tin MelodyNet. Our ablation baseline RPPNet-RandomGrouped isolates the contribution of perceptual semantics\n343\tfrom mere variable-length grouping, yielding a clean controlled comparison: fixed-bar (Museformer, MELONS)\n344\tvs. perceptually-grouped variable-length (RPPNet) vs.\n345\trandomly-grouped variable-length (ablation).\n346\t4.3 Experiment Setup\n347\t4.3.1 Objective Metrics\n348\tTo validate the effectiveness of RPP grouping, we construct a random-grouping baseline (Random-Grouped) that\n349\tpreserves the length distribution of the RPP training set via\n350\trandom sampling while removing structural semantics.\n351\tFollowing Museformer [15], we adopt Perplexity (PPL)\n352\tand Structural Error (SE) as objective metrics. This alignment isolates the effect of structural representation choice\n353\tfrom metric selection bias. PPL requires a consistent vocabulary across models, so Museformer and MELONS are\n354\texcluded from the objective comparison. We also note\n355\tgrowing evidence questioning the perceptual validity of\n356\tconventional symbolic music objective metrics [50].\n357\tWe further verify the RPP-level generator’s learning of\n358\tunderlying distributions by comparing attribute statistics\n359\tbetween ground-truth and generated RPP sequences.\n360\t4.3.2 Subjective Metrics\n361\tFollowing [49], we conduct a subjective listening test with\n362\t15 paid participants (7 with musical background, 8 without) rating generated melodies on a 10-point scale (1—10).\n363\tAll models are trained from scratch, yielding 50 32-bar\n364\tmelodies evaluated across five configurations—RPPNet,\n365\tRPPNet-Real, RPPNet-Random-Grouped, Museformer,\n366\tand MELONS—alongside 10 human-composed references from the test set.\n367\tParticipants were asked to rate each melody on a scale\n368\tof 1–10 (lowest to highest) along the following four dimensions:\n369\t• Coherence: Is the melody fluent, pleasant, and engaging?\n370\t\n371\t• Rhythmicity: Does the melody exhibit a regular metric pattern and appropriate use of rests?\n372\t• Structure: Does the melody display clear structural\n373\tfeatures, such as reasonable repetition and motivic\n374\tdevelopment?\n375\t• Overall Impression: A holistic evaluation of the\n376\tmelody.\n377\tWe select Museformer [15] and MELONS [17] as primary baselines, both representing fixed bar-level structural modeling that our work relaxes. MelodyGLM\n378\t[49] is excluded as its pretrain-finetune paradigm introduces a confounding variable unrelated to boundary\n379\tdesign. PhraseLDM [36] is excluded due to its reliance on explicit phrase annotations unavailable in MelodyNet. The ablation baseline RPPNet-Random-Grouped\n380\tisolates perceptual semantics from variable-length grouping alone, enabling a controlled comparison across fixedbar, perceptually-grouped, and randomly-grouped conditions.\n381\t5. RESULT\n382\t5.1 Statistic Analysis\n383\tTo quantify RPP-level distributional fidelity, we statistically compare real and generated attribute distributions,\n384\tyielding a Pearson correlation of 92.19% across 23 categories (Table 2). Dimension-level analysis reveals strong\n385\talignment in note group (r = 0.98) and melodic contour\n386\t(r = 0.90), while rhythm pattern shows the largest gap\n387\t(r = 0.44), primarily due to over-generation of iambs (0,1:\n388\t+15.5%) and under-generation of trochees (1,0: −11.4%).\n389\tThese results suggest the model effectively captures note\n390\tgrouping and pitch contour structure, while rhythmic pattern fidelity remains the primary direction for improvement.\n391\t5.2 Ablation Study\n392\tTo validate the effectiveness of heuristic RPP grouping, we\n393\tconstruct a random-grouping ablation baseline (RandomGrouped) within the RPPNet framework with aligned\n394\tlength distribution. Objective metrics (Table 3) show that\n395\tstandard RPPNet (P P L = 2.21, SE = 0.0132) outperforms Random-Grouped (2.36, 0.0175).\n396\tSubjective evaluation (Table 1) further reveals that\n397\tRandom-Grouped exhibits significant degradation across\n398\tall dimensions upon removing heuristic grouping: coherence (5.99, p<0.001), rhythmic quality (6.08, p < 0.01),\n399\tstructural quality (6.01, p < 0.001), and overall impression (6.09, p < 0.01). This demonstrates that the structural semantics captured by heuristic grouping are critical\n400\tfor melodic coherence and motif organization.\n401\tMeanwhile, standard RPPNet and RPPNet-Real\n402\t(ground-truth RPP input) show no significant difference\n403\tin coherence (6.61 vs. 6.61, p = 1.00), rhythmic quality\n404\t(6.61 vs. 6.59, p = 0.93), or overall impression (6.69 vs.\n405\t6.61, p = 0.55), with structural quality also approaching\n406\t\n407\t\fModel\n408\t\n409\tCoherence\n410\t\n411\tRhythmicity\n412\t∗∗\n413\t\n414\tHuman\n415\t\n416\t7.29 ± 0.74\n417\t\n418\tRPPNet (Ours)\n419\tRPPNet-Real\n420\tRPPNet-Rnd-Grp\n421\tMuseformer [15]\n422\tMELONS [17]\n423\t\n424\t6.61 ± 0.71\n425\t6.61 ± 0.85\n426\t5.99 ± 0.62∗∗∗\n427\t5.81 ± 0.54∗∗∗\n428\t5.39 ± 0.69∗∗∗\n429\t\n430\tStructure\n431\t\n432\t∗∗\n433\t\n434\tOverall\n435\t\n436\t7.36 ± 0.68\n437\t\n438\t∗∗\n439\t\n440\t7.45 ± 0.82\n441\t\n442\t7.47 ± 0.79∗∗\n443\t\n444\t6.61 ± 0.69\n445\t6.59 ± 0.83\n446\t6.08 ± 0.54∗∗\n447\t5.62 ± 0.53∗∗∗\n448\t5.33 ± 0.66∗∗∗\n449\t\n450\t6.77 ± 0.73\n451\t6.51 ± 0.98\n452\t6.01 ± 0.64∗∗∗\n453\t5.57 ± 0.58∗∗∗\n454\t5.31 ± 0.76∗∗∗\n455\t\n456\t6.69 ± 0.68\n457\t6.61 ± 0.87\n458\t6.09 ± 0.66∗∗\n459\t5.73 ± 0.54∗∗∗\n460\t5.30 ± 0.77∗∗∗\n461\t\n462\tTable 1. Results of the subjective evaluation. Scores are presented as Mean ± Standard Deviation. Asterisks denote\n463\tsignificant differences compared to our proposed RPPNet (∗∗ p < 0.01, ∗∗∗ p < 0.001). “Overall” denotes the overall\n464\tmusical impression.\n465\tAttribute / Pattern\n466\t\n467\tReal (%)\n468\t\n469\tGenerated (%)\n470\t\n471\tNote Group\n472\tOne note\n473\tTwo notes\n474\tThree notes\n475\t\n476\t12.26\n477\t36.25\n478\t51.49\n479\t\n480\t10.61\n481\t40.41\n482\t48.98\n483\t\n484\tRhythm Pattern\n485\t(0,)\n486\t(1,)\n487\t(0, 1)\n488\t(1, 0)\n489\t(0, 0, 1)\n490\t(0, 1, 0)\n491\t(1, 0, 0)\n492\t\n493\t7.74\n494\t4.51\n495\t14.29\n496\t21.96\n497\t14.14\n498\t17.72\n499\t19.64\n500\t\n501\t8.43\n502\t2.19\n503\t29.83\n504\t10.57\n505\t16.31\n506\t17.18\n507\t15.49\n508\t\n509\tMelodic Contour\n510\tDescending\n511\tAscending\n512\tStationary\n513\tCont. Descending\n514\tCont. Ascending\n515\tCont. Stationary\n516\tDown then Up\n517\tUp then Down\n518\tStay then Up\n519\tStay then Down\n520\tDown then Stay\n521\tUp then Stay\n522\tSingle Note\n523\t\n524\t15.47\n525\t13.18\n526\t7.60\n527\t7.68\n528\t7.26\n529\t6.32\n530\t8.93\n531\t10.11\n532\t2.85\n533\t3.30\n534\t2.51\n535\t2.54\n536\t12.26\n537\t\n538\t15.15\n539\t18.19\n540\t7.06\n541\t6.83\n542\t6.28\n543\t3.25\n544\t8.91\n545\t8.15\n546\t4.46\n547\t3.98\n548\t3.74\n549\t3.39\n550\t10.61\n551\t\n552\tTable 2. Detailed statistical distributions of note density,\n553\trhythm pattern, and melodic contour across real and generated datasets.\n554\tnon-significance (6.77 vs. 6.51, p = 0.08). This suggests\n555\tthat the RPP-level generator of RPPNet possesses strong\n556\tdistribution fitting capabilities, corroborating the findings\n557\tfrom statistical experiments.\n558\t5.3 Comparison with Previous Models\n559\tTable 1 presents the subjective ratings and significance\n560\ttests against baselines. Human-composed melodies score\n561\t7.47 overall as the reference ceiling. RPPNet achieves\n562\tan overall impression of 6.69, significantly outperforming Museformer (5.73, p < 0.001) and Melons (5.30,\n563\tp < 0.001). The advantage is most pronounced in structural quality: RPPNet (6.77) exceeds Museformer (5.57,\n564\tp < 0.001) and MELONS (5.31, p < 0.001) by 1.20 and\n565\t1.46 points, respectively, demonstrating that explicit hierarchical structural modeling effectively enhances the organization of long-term structure.\n566\t\n567\tModel\n568\t\n569\tPPL ↓\n570\t\n571\tSE ↓\n572\t\n573\tRPPNet (Ours)\n574\tRPPNet-Random-Grouped\n575\t\n576\t2.21\n577\t2.36\n578\t\n579\t0.0132 ± 0.0013\n580\t0.0175 ± 0.0008\n581\t\n582\tTable 3. Results of the objective evaluation in the ablation\n583\tstudy. SE denotes the structural entropy of Rhythmic Pattern Primitives (RPPs). The best results are highlighted in\n584\tbold.\n585\t6. DISCUSSION\n586\tThis work integrates music-psychological principles with\n587\tmusic theory to propose RPPNet, a perception-driven\n588\tstructural representation for melody generation that transcends fixed bar-level boundaries through hierarchical decoupled generation. Experiments confirm that this framework significantly outperforms existing baselines in longterm structural coherence and overall musicality.\n589\tThese results demonstrate that perception-driven grouping significantly outperforms fixed bar-level representations. Ablation experiments reveal that performance gains\n590\tstem from the proper encoding of perceptual grouping\n591\tprinciples—merely breaking bar isometry without respecting perceptual rules yields no benefit.\n592\tAlthough RPPNet significantly outperforms existing\n593\tbaselines, a quality gap remains compared to human compositions (overall 7.47vs.6.69), likely attributable to the\n594\tdistributional mismatch in rhythmic patterns (Pearson r =\n595\t0.44). Closing this gap is the central challenge going forward.\n596\tFuture work will proceed along three directions: (1)\n597\thybrid data-driven and rule-driven structural strategies;\n598\t(2) introducing micro-macro feedback mechanisms where\n599\tNote-level generation revises RPP-level structure; and (3)\n600\textending this representation to polyphonic music and accompaniment generation, evaluating its capability under\n601\tcomplex musical textures.\n602\t7. REFERENCES\n603\t[1] S. Ji, X. Yang, and J. Luo, “A survey on deep learning\n604\tfor symbolic music generation: Representations, algorithms, evaluations, and challenges,” ACM Computing\n605\tSurveys, vol. 56, no. 1, pp. 1–39, 2023.\n606\t[2] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve, Y. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and control-\n607\t\n608\t\flable music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36, pp. 47 704–47 720,\n609\t2023.\n610\t[3] J. Liang, H. Zhang, H. Liu, Y. Cao, Q. Kong,\n611\tX. Liu, W. Wang, M. D. Plumbley, H. Phan,\n612\tand E. Benetos, “Wavcraft: Audio editing and\n613\tgeneration with large language models,” in ICLR 2024\n614\tWorkshop on LLM Agents, 2024. [Online]. Available:\n615\thttps://openreview.net/forum?id=xJw7x2ZBex\n616\t[4] H. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Yuan, X. Mei, X. Liu, D. Mandic,\n617\tW. Wang, and M. D. Plumbley, “Audioldm: Text-toaudio generation with latent diffusion models,” arXiv\n618\tpreprint arXiv:2301.12503, 2023.\n619\t[5] J.-P. Briot and F. Pachet, “Deep learning for music generation: Challenges and direction